12
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:30,080
Sorry, I only asked.

13
00:00:30,080 --> 00:00:32,119
Don't worry, I wasn't really upset.

14
00:00:32,119 --> 00:00:35,200
I just wanted to demonstrate the meaning of the word.

15
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:38,799
The word snowflake has taken on a new meaning in recent years.

16
00:00:38,799 --> 00:00:41,320
These days, it's used as an insult.

17
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:44,000
It's used to criticise people or groups

18
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,560
that are seen to be very easily offended

19
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:48,640
or upset by things that others say.

20
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:52,000
There is usually a political side to it, too, isn't there?

21
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:54,719
Yes, people who use the word snowflake

22
00:00:54,719 --> 00:00:57,039
tend to be from the political right

23
00:00:57,079 --> 00:01:00,519
and they usually use it about those on the political left,

24
00:01:00,519 --> 00:01:04,239
particularly millennials, young, socially aware adults.

25
00:01:04,239 --> 00:01:06,879
Well, we'll explore this topic in more detail shortly,

26
00:01:06,879 --> 00:01:09,120
but first, a quiz question,

27
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:11,079
in which year was snowflake

28
00:01:11,079 --> 00:01:14,120
one of Colin's dictionaries words of the year?

29
00:01:14,120 --> 00:01:21,079
Was it a 1996, B, 2006, or C, 2016?

30
00:01:21,079 --> 00:01:22,840
Well, we said it's quite a recent word,

31
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:25,439
so I'm going for C, 2016.

32
00:01:25,439 --> 00:01:28,599
Well, we'll find out if you're right later on in the programme.

33
00:01:28,599 --> 00:01:31,719
The topic of offence is a very complicated one.

34
00:01:31,719 --> 00:01:34,640
First, what do we mean by offence, Rob?

35
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:35,799
Thanks for that.

36
00:01:35,799 --> 00:01:38,200
That is a really difficult question.

37
00:01:38,200 --> 00:01:40,400
Something that is offensive is rude,

38
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:43,840
insulting and makes people feel hurt and upset.

39
00:01:43,840 --> 00:01:45,719
What's difficult about it, though,

40
00:01:45,719 --> 00:01:49,120
is that we don't all find the same things offensive.

41
00:01:49,120 --> 00:01:50,959
Some people can be deliberately offensive

42
00:01:50,959 --> 00:01:53,920
and some people may be offensive without meaning to be.

43
00:01:53,960 --> 00:01:57,280
Also, different people respond to offence in different ways.

44
00:01:57,280 --> 00:02:00,000
Some accept it as the price of free speech

45
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:03,040
and some try to stop the people they think are offensive

46
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:04,840
from saying the things they do.

47
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:07,439
These terms come up quite a lot in discussions

48
00:02:07,439 --> 00:02:10,879
about equality, race, religion and, of course, politics.

49
00:02:10,879 --> 00:02:14,240
The topic was discussed in detail in the BBC Radio programme,

50
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:15,520
Sweet Reason.

51
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:17,240
Evan Davis presented the programme,

52
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:20,639
and here is the first part of his summary of the discussion.

53
00:02:20,639 --> 00:02:22,360
What does he say is the reason

54
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:25,040
that some people talk about offence?

55
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:28,880
First, on occasion, people probably do invoke offence,

56
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:31,200
when really they just have a political disagreement,

57
00:02:31,200 --> 00:02:33,520
and on occasion, groups that suffer discrimination

58
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:36,360
or exclusion, perhaps find it exhilarating

59
00:02:36,360 --> 00:02:40,920
or uniting to call out that discrimination.

60
00:02:40,920 --> 00:02:43,320
He says that some people take offence

61
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:45,400
when it's just a political disagreement.

62
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:47,200
He says they invoke offence.

63
00:02:47,200 --> 00:02:50,400
If you invoke something, it means that you use it

64
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:53,280
to support your point or explain your action.

65
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:57,319
So to invoke offence is to say that we are acting this way

66
00:02:57,319 --> 00:03:00,040
because we are offended by what you've said.

67
00:03:00,040 --> 00:03:02,800
Although the offence may only be a political difference

68
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:05,159
rather than something truly offensive.

69
00:03:05,159 --> 00:03:08,000
Davis goes on to say that groups that do suffer

70
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,400
from discrimination may get some feelings of unity

71
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,800
when they call out discrimination.

72
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:16,080
They feel more together when they publicise

73
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:19,240
and highlight the discrimination they've experienced.

74
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:22,280
Even though some offence that is taken may not be genuine,

75
00:03:22,280 --> 00:03:25,280
that doesn't mean people don't have a right to be offended.

76
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:27,080
He's Evan Davis again.

77
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:30,719
Where the so-called snowflakes surely have a point is this.

78
00:03:30,719 --> 00:03:34,760
Societies are entitled to make certain things taboo,

79
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:36,800
and the millennial's use of the word offensive

80
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:39,439
is simply designed to say some views are not just wrong,

81
00:03:39,439 --> 00:03:42,240
they're in a special category wrong.

82
00:03:42,240 --> 00:03:45,520
His point here is that societies can decide

83
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:47,719
that certain things are taboo.

84
00:03:47,719 --> 00:03:49,919
In this context, something that is taboo

85
00:03:49,919 --> 00:03:52,159
is something that is regarded by society

86
00:03:52,159 --> 00:03:54,520
as being shocking and offensive,

87
00:03:54,520 --> 00:03:57,719
and that it's okay for people to be offended by these things.

88
00:03:57,719 --> 00:04:00,000
And I think the point he makes is a good one.

89
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,360
The word snowflake is usually used as an insult,

90
00:04:03,360 --> 00:04:06,079
but some people may feel proud to be a snowflake

91
00:04:06,079 --> 00:04:09,719
because it means they're standing up for a particular standard.

92
00:04:09,719 --> 00:04:12,960
They have a level of decency and social responsibility

93
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:17,120
that is higher than that of those who are calling them snowflakes.

94
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:20,399
Well, I hope we haven't caused any offense today.

95
00:04:20,399 --> 00:04:21,959
Before we review the vocabulary,

96
00:04:21,959 --> 00:04:24,720
